{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"136f4756-ac66-4747-bf11-84333b9bc81c","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is exactly what you need to bring workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — reinstalls the **same versions** already recorded. It fixes corrupted or partially-installed workloads but won't pull newer versions required by the updated SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf the build still fails afterward, also try `dotnet workload restore` in your project directory — it will install any workloads declared in your project's `global.json` or workload manifests.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7c33f79a-27e2-4af0-b604-f66b5e142628","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":252},"id":"411e9c24-aeba-42bb-9b05-8f598825af72","timestamp":"2026-04-09T15:16:46.970Z","parentId":"628cc90e-564c-4222-af00-1e0883a54922"}
